1. e4 { [%clk 1:30:57] } 1... c5 { [%clk 1:30:45] } 2. Nf3 { [%clk 1:31:19] } 2... e6 { [%clk 1:31:08] } 3. d4 { [%clk 1:31:43] } 3... cxd4 { [%clk 1:31:33] } 4. Nxd4 { [%clk 1:32:09] } 4... Nc6 { [%clk 1:31:53] } 5. Nc3 { [%clk 1:32:32] } 5... Qc7 { [%clk 1:32:17] } 6. Ncb5!? { A small surprise which my opponent had not played before in any published games. I had checked this line briefly the morning before the game, because I thought it was a possible "surprise weapon" that has recently been trendy at the top level. I had played this with white in Qatar several months ago with good success. Unfortunately my preparation with black was a bit limited as we'll see... } { [%clk 1:32:41] } 6... Qb8 { [%clk 1:32:20] } 7. Bd3 { [%clk 1:32:47] } 7... Nf6 { [%clk 1:32:43] } 8. O-O { [%clk 1:32:38] } 8... a6 { [%clk 1:32:57] } 9. Nxc6 { [%clk 1:32:49] } 9... bxc6 { [%clk 1:33:12] } 10. Nc3 { A natural move, but deviating from my pre-game prep. } { [%clk 1:33:13] } (10. Nd4 { I had only checked this move before the game as it's the engine's top suggestion. } 10... c5 11. Nf3 c4 12. Bxc4 Nxe4 13. Qd4 Nf6 { This is what I was looking at before the game. White has some initiative, but the position should be very playable for black. }) 10... d5 { [%clk 1:31:08] } 11. Qe2 { [%clk 1:32:46] } 11... Be7 { [%clk 1:26:50] } 12. b3 { I only realized after the game why my opponent played b3. The Queen on b8 pressures the b2 pawn, so white ensures the pawn is defended before developing the bishop! During the game, I thought white just wants to play Bb2, but my opponent had other intentions... } { [%clk 1:32:17] } 12... O-O { [%clk 1:24:54] } 13. Bd2 { [%clk 1:32:22] } 13... Re8 { [%clk 1:23:14] } 14. Rae1 { [%clk 1:26:20] } 14... Bb7 { [%clk 1:20:14] } (14... c5 15. e5 Nd7 16. f4 { I didn't want to go for this because with the pawn committed to c5, I can't play Nc5. }) 15. f4 { [%clk 1:19:35] } (15. e5 Nd7 16. f4 Nc5 { Forcing the trade of white's light-squared bishop should lead to a safer position for black }) 15... dxe4 { [%clk 1:06:04] } 16. Nxe4 { [%clk 1:19:18] } 16... c5 { [%clk 1:06:07] } 17. Ng5 { [%clk 1:13:20] } 17... Qd6 { [%clk 0:59:14] } (17... h6 18. Nxf7 Kxf7 19. Qxe6+ Kf8 20. Bc4 $18) 18. Bc3 { [%clk 1:01:11] } 18... h6 { [%clk 0:58:18] } 19. Be5 { [%clk 0:59:50] } 19... Qb6 { [%clk 0:56:21] } 20. c4 { Somehow I did not anticipate this move } { [%clk 0:58:55] } 20... Rad8 { [%clk 0:50:47] } 21. Bb1 { [%clk 0:54:01] } 21... Qc6 { [%clk 0:43:14] } (21... hxg5 22. fxg5 Qa5! { This is the engine's suggestion, which I didn't consider. Black threatens Rd2 to target white's queen and g2-pawn. This looks incredibly complicated and the engine gives 0.00. Surely, there's more to analyze here } 23. Rf2 Ng4 24. Rxf7 Qxe1+ 25. Qxe1 Kxf7 26. Qe2 Nxe5 27. Qh5+ Kf8 28. Qh8+ Kf7 29. Qh5+ $10) (21... Qa5) 22. Ba1 { [%clk 0:37:55] } 22... Qxg2+ { Played after a 30-minute think } { [%clk 0:13:27] } (22... hxg5 { I spent a long time determining whether this capture could be possible, but it should have been pretty easy to reject after the following line: } 23. fxg5 Nh5 24. Bh7+ Kh8 25. Be4 Qxe4 26. Qxh5+ Qh7 27. Bxg7+ Kxg7 28. Rxf7+) (22... Qb6 { Ironically, the engine wants this } 23. Nf3 Nd7) (22... Nd7? 23. Bh7+ Kf8 24. Be4 Qb6 25. Qh5 $18) 23. Qxg2 { [%clk 0:38:17] } 23... Bxg2 { [%clk 0:13:55] } 24. Kxg2 { [%clk 0:38:01] } 24... hxg5 { [%clk 0:13:34] } 25. fxg5 { [%clk 0:38:25] } 25... Nh5 { [%clk 0:11:11] } 26. g6 { [%clk 0:34:29] } 26... Rd2+ { [%clk 0:10:54] } 27. Kh3 { [%clk 0:34:16] } 27... Bf6? { Probably the losing mistake of the game, completely. missing my opponent's next move. } { [%clk 0:09:55] } 28. Re5!! { [%clk 0:29:47] } 28... Rf8? { not the best attempt to defend } { [%clk 0:01:16] } (28... fxg6 { I had calculated the following during the game and concluded it would be lost. That's why I went for 28...Rf8. } 29. Bxg6 Bxe5 30. Bxe5 Nf6 31. Bxf6 Rf8 32. Bg5 Rxf1 33. Bxd2 { my calculations ended here, but I should have dug deeper. } 33... Rf2 34. Bg5 Rxa2 35. Be8 { The only move to keep an edge. White intends Ba4 to hold onto b3. } 35... Rc2 36. Ba4 { This should be winning for white, but it takes a lot more work compared to what happened in the game. }) 29. Rxh5 { [%clk 0:28:14] } 29... Bxa1 { [%clk 0:01:44] } 30. gxf7+ { [%clk 0:28:24] } 30... Rxf7 { [%clk 0:02:13] } 31. Bh7+ { [%clk 0:28:46] } 31... Kf8 { [%clk 0:02:36] } 32. Rxa1 { [%clk 0:29:08] } 32... Rf3+ { [%clk 0:00:39] } 33. Kg4 { [%clk 0:29:17] } 33... Rff2 { [%clk 0:00:39] } 34. Be4 { [%clk 0:27:42] } 34... Rfe2 { [%clk 0:00:32] } 35. Bf3 { [%clk 0:25:53] } 35... Rxh2 { [%clk 0:00:35] } 36. Rxc5 { [%clk 0:25:17] } 36... Rh6 { [%clk 0:00:32] } 37. Rd1 { [%clk 0:22:48] } 37... Rxa2 { [%clk 0:00:32] } 38. Rc7 { [%clk 0:21:44] } 38... Rg6+ { [%clk 0:00:35] } 39. Kf4 { [%clk 0:22:03] } 39... Rf6+ { [%clk 0:00:52] } 40. Ke3 { A tough loss to start the tournament. Takeaways:
I should have been way more prepared for this Ncb5 line in the Taimanov
My calculation/ability to consider candidate moves was lacking in this game. } { [%clk 0:22:28] } *


